ity=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230812_wot125.png 960w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1096,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230812_wot125.png 1096w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1280,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230812_wot125.png 1280w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230812_wot125.png 1424w" src="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230812_wot125.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></figure></section><figure> <span itemscope="" itemprop="image" itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject" data-slim="0"><img loading="lazy" src="https://www.economist.com/img/b/1280/2788/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230812_wof125.png" srcset="https://www.economist.com/img/b/200/436/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230812_wof125.png 200w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/300/653/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230812_wof125.png 300w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/400/871/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230812_wof125.png 400w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/600/1307/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230812_wof125.png 600w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/640/1394/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230812_wof125.png 640w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/800/1743/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230812_wof125.png 800w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/1000/2178/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230812_wof125.png 1000w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/1280/2788/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230812_wof125.png 1280w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 640px, 95vw" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></span></figure><p class="article__body-text"><span>贫穷国家的学童在标准化考试中的表现比富裕国家的学童差。他们血液中的铅含量也高出十倍。美国智库全球发展中心（CGD）的研究人员在一份新的工作论文中认为，仅铅中毒就造成了富国和穷国之间学习差距的五分之一。贫穷国家的孩子们因多种原因而受到阻碍，但铅中毒的认知负担使学习变得更加困难，而且可能是最容易应对的挑战。</span></p><p class="article__body-text"><span>世界各国政府都禁止使用的含铅汽油已不再是问题。但铅仍然潜伏在贫穷国家的其他地方。南亚一半的儿童和非洲近 40% 的儿童血液中铅含量升高。铅暴露会改变大脑中神经递质的释放，并与注意力持续时间较短、智力较低和反社会行为有关。研究人员利用世界银行的一系列“统一学习成果”表明，如果铅中毒问题能够达到美国的水平，发展中国家和发达国家之间的学习差距将缩小 21%。</span></p> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> /内容/phkkqjq2j455o4qf1e279gv5v2r91fj5</guid><link/> https://www.economist.com/espressochart/2023<category>不确定</category><category>联合国</category><category>刚果民主共和国</category><category>埃塞俄比亚</category><category>印度</category><category>尼日利亚</category><category>巴基斯坦</category><category>中国</category><category>人口增长</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Grocery dominance in the digital age]]></title><description><![CDATA[<section class="css-1ugvd2u e1y6i3a60"><style data-emotion="css j1vyw6">.css-j1vyw6 img{display:block;}.css-j1vyw6 .e16qazw92{margin-top:0.25rem;}</style><figure class="css-j1vyw6 e12yhaj20"><img alt="佛罗里达州一家沃尔玛的购物者在收银台拍照。" fetchpriority="high" width="1280" height="720" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" sizes="(min-width: 960px) 700px, 95vw" srcset="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=360,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230812_PDP506.jpg 360w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=384,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230812_PDP506.jpg 384w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=480,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230812_PDP506.jpg 480w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=600,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230812_PDP506.jpg 600w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=834,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230812_PDP506.jpg 834w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=960,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230812_PDP506.jpg 960w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1096,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230812_PDP506.jpg 1096w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1280,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230812_PDP506.jpg 1280w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230812_PDP506.jpg 1424w" src="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230812_PDP506.jpg" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></figure></section><p class="article__body-text">杂货购物是一项巨大的财富——占美国每年约 8000 亿美元的支出。但这也是一项众所周知的艰难业务，对价格敏感的客户严格控制利润。再加上在线送货，它往往变得无利可图。对于像亚马逊这样的数字原生公司来说，说服顾客在网上购买更多的杂货是其圣杯，而亚马逊是该行业的新手。但亚马逊的“技术第一”方针还不足以赢得市场，也不足以赢得仍然看到店内购物价值的顾客。这使得像沃尔玛这样的杂货巨头有机会在网上扩张，同时利用他们在实体店的立足点。利润如此之低，但便利性的诱惑却如此之大，网上杂货购物的未来会怎样？</p><p class="article__body-text">在本周的播客中，主持人汤姆·李-德夫林、爱丽丝·福尔伍德和迈克·伯德探讨了杂货业如何适应数字时代。麦肯锡北美零售和消费者业务负责人比尔·奥尔 (Bill Aull) 解释了在线杂货购物如何在美国难以取得成功。作者贾森·德尔雷 (Jason Del Rey) 阐述了亚马逊和沃尔玛之间的战斗告诉我们该行业的未来方向。片长39分钟</p><p class="article__body-text"><iframe height="215" src="https://embed.acast.com/theeconomistmoneytalks/money-talks-click-and-collect-a-grocery-victory" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></p><p class="article__body-text">请访问<a href="https://www.economist.com/moneytalks/" data-tegid="s3jdjo7ltifmvd584dj833vriomahkr5">www.economist.com/moneytalks</a>订阅我们新的每周通讯，剖析市场、商业和经济的重大主题</p><p class="article__body-text">要完全访问印刷版、数字版和音频版，请订阅<i>《经济学人》</i> ： <a href="https://www.economist.com/podcastoffer/">www.economist.com/podcastoffer</a></p><p class="article__body-text">收听： <a href="https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/id420929545">Apple 播客</a>| <a href="https://open.spotify.com/show/2Yvo8QxZf7WlSEsIwKjtX4">Spotify</a> | <a href="https://podcasts.google.com/feed/aHR0cHM6Ly9yc3MuYWNhc3QuY29tL3RoZWVjb25vbWlzdG1vbmV5dGFsa3M">谷歌</a>|<a href="https://www.stitcher.com/show/the-economist-money-talks">缝合器</a>| <a href="https://tunein.com/podcasts/Business--